CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260720T091332Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credit: Arun Prasad's Comic Archive\nJoin us for a special Indian Sign Language-interpreted\, Deaf-led guided walk of A Moving Line.\n\nLed by Akanksha Kamble from the MAP team\, this session centres on Deaf perspectives\, with Indian Sign Language (ISL) as the primary language of engagement\, offering a visual-first\, inclusive approach to experiencing the exhibition.\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. 
DTEND:20260726T113000Z
DTSTART:20260726T103000Z
SUMMARY:Signing Illustrations - ISL Guided Walk
UID:1346@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/signing-illustrations-isl-guided-walk/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Screenshot-2026-07-15-200131.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260716T130256Z
DESCRIPTION:A Moving Line gathers more than 250 works to trace how India has told stories in sequence across fifteen hundred years. Come\, witness both the creation of new visual identities and the evolution of a nation through a vast body of works across time and space as Khushi Bansal from the MAP team guides you through it. Follow a single line from a temple wall in Bengaluru to the touchscreen\, and watch a country tell its stories.\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. 
DTEND:20260726T083000Z
DTSTART:20260726T073000Z
SUMMARY:Panels\, Pages and Presentations
UID:1343@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/panels-pages-and-presentations/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Sankha-Banerjee--scaled.jpg
CATEGORIES:Workshops,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260723T050240Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credits: Birla Academy of Art and Culture\nIf you've ever wanted to try your hand at making a comic\, this is your chance! Join graphic novelist Sankha Banerjee for a hands-on session where you'll learn the basics\, sketch your ideas\, learn sequential storytelling and create your very first comic!\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling.
DTEND:20260725T060000Z
DTSTART:20260725T043000Z
SUMMARY:Pow\, Kaboom\, Create!
UID:1355@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/pow-kaboom-create/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Screenshot-2026-07-15-192302.png
CATEGORIES:Panel Discussion,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260722T050711Z
DESCRIPTION:Image Credits: Panels from Will to Live by Mia Jose\nComic artist Mia Jose\, comic book writer Pierre Dawance and graphic novelist Simon Lamouret will converse about their experiences and the inspirations that led them to create their works. This session focuses on identity\, culture and the city\, drawing on their individual practices and the spaces their works are rooted in. The notion of city is rooted in some of their works\, which helps us see a space as one’s company\, a space of constant changes and as identity. Get to know about their thought processes\, artistic inspirations and how the country they grew up in influenced their works. \n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling.
DTEND:20260725T123000Z
DTSTART:20260725T113000Z
SUMMARY:Artist-in-Dialogue
UID:1340@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/artist-in-dialogue/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/6761a8d5-7abc-4ece-9177-6c5d56422bd4-e1784286828237.jpg
CATEGORIES:Performances,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260717T115359Z
DESCRIPTION:Image credit: Sonia Dechamps\nJoin graphic novelist David Prudhomme for a live drawing performance accompanied by a selection of music chosen by the artist. As images unfold in real time\, Prudhomme invites audiences into the intimate relationship between sound\, memory\, and visual storytelling.\n\nThe performance will be followed by a talk on his work\, with a focus on the role of music in his graphic novels. Music is central to Rébétiko and Rébétissa (Futuropolis)\, his two-part exploration of the outlawed Greek musical tradition of the 1930s and the histories\, communities\, and cultural landscapes it emerged from.\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. 
DTEND:20260726T103000Z
DTSTART:20260726T093000Z
SUMMARY:Live Drawing
UID:1352@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/live-drawing/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Book_mockup.png
CATEGORIES:Book Launch,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260721T051241Z
DESCRIPTION:Join us for the launch of MAP’s latest publication\, A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling\, a first of its kind anthology tracing India’s long and rich history of visual storytelling\, from temple walls and painted scrolls to comics\, graphic novels\, and webcomics.\n\nThe book launch is followed by a panel discussion with graphic artist and researcher Sarita Sundar\, comics archivist and researcher Arun Prasad\, publication designer Mira Malhotra and artist Partha Banik\, moderated by Saba Nehal from the MAP team.\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling.
DTEND:20260725T103000Z
DTSTART:20260725T093000Z
SUMMARY:A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling
UID:1348@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/a-moving-line-1500-years-of-indian-visual-storytelling/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/Screenshot-2026-07-15-202955.png
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260717T073554Z
DESCRIPTION:Do you remember Shikari Shambu? What about Suppandi? We’ve all read stories of these beloved comic characters but do you wonder how they were created? Who drew them\; what stories that came before inspired their creators\; Did their designs change? Join us for a guided walk in Kannada led by Niharika Shenoy from the MAP team to wonder about these and more questions. Get a sneak peek into the curatorial perspective and the history of Indian visual storytelling.\n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. 
DTEND:20260725T113000Z
DTSTART:20260725T103000Z
SUMMARY:Ink mattu kathe - A Kannada Guided Walk
UID:1345@map-india.org
URL:https://map-india.org/map-events/ink-mattu-kathe-a-kannada-guided-walk/
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
ATTACH;FMTTYPE=image/jpeg:https://map-india.org/wp-content/uploads/2026/07/TC.2025.005-1-scaled.jpeg
CATEGORIES:Guided Walk,MAP,CBD
DTSTAMP:20260723T082251Z
DESCRIPTION:Image: Courtesy of Priyanka Paul\nJoin us for a guided walkthrough of the A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling as its curator Amruta Patil narrates the stories this country tells through lines. In this exhibition\, one can witness both the creation of new visual identities and the evolution of a nation through a vast body of works across time and space. Here\, kaavad and pattachitra scroll sitting alongside Amar Chitra Katha and Tinkle. Chacha Chaudhary next to the Phantom\, while contemporary graphic novels and web comics continue conversations that began centuries ago. \n\nThis programme is part of the celebration of the opening of A Moving Line: 1500 Years of Indian Visual Storytelling. 
DTEND:20260726T053000Z
DTSTART:20260726T043000Z
